Anonymous Wed 27 Jan 2021 06:14:09 No.35858867 Report
Quoted By: >>35859108
>>35852559
Figured I'd post this in the new thread as writing advice. When I write dialogue I first set up the interaction, and think about what I want out of a scene, even if the goal is something as simple as it being funny. Then I think about what the characters would want out of an interaction, and I follow that to a T. It often makes character interactions longer than I set up on my outline, and it can be inconvenient. Sometimes I'll just change stuff up from my outline on the spot if it doesn't fit well, I'm using it as more of a guideline anyway. Don't know if this'll interest anyone, but I've never really analyzed how I write much and that could be a useful exercise.

>>35858867
Hmm.
I've said I usually start with one of a few things, but most boil down to what I want to learn/show in a scene.
Whether the characters are antagonistic or not, I 'm less concerned about what they're doing and how they're interacting than what they say. Reconstructing a flow of agreements and evasions from a conversation is easier than writing dialogue to fit some preconceived setpiece.

But that's just me.
Whatever piece a writer does first, it should be the one that allows them to color in the rest of the scene later.

Yeah, I never have scenes completely thought out before I start writing. I've also found that keeping an evolving profile on each of my main characters helps with continuity and makes it easier to write if I'm having trouble thinking of how they would respond to a situation. Evolving meaning, when I define something new about a character I add it to their profile. But having something like that to refer back to is really useful. If I'm really hard up, I'll sometimes revisit scenes I've already written and use those as a guideline.
